items.name: Ancient Cross
items.description: Images from the Pagan past conflict and co-exist with Christian symbolism in the carvings on many early cross shafts. The cross was a Pagan symbol long before it was a Christian one and the familiar cross in a circle is actually an ancient sun disc that has been carved in stone since the Bronze Age. Writhing serpents, ancient gods, foliage, rosettes and sun spirals are all to be found alongside strange interpretations of the crucifixion. Leaning broken by a stile or standing proudly in a churchyard, hidden in a tangled hedgerow or high on a bleak moor, these crosses waymark the passage from Paganism to Christianity.

items.name: Ancient Trackway
items.description: A pre-Roman road or track

items.name: Ancient Village or Settlement
items.description: Included in this category are remains of habitated areas of all sorts, including cattle pens. There is a separate listing for crannogs.

items.name: Artificial Mound
items.description: A man-made mound which is not a burial chamber.

items.name: Barrow Cemetery
items.description: A collection of round barrows, long barrows etc. Usually a sacred area used over thousands of years for burials.

items.name: Broch or Nuraghe
items.description: An Iron Age stone structure, also known as a roundhouse. Built throughout Scotland, concentrated near the coasts, as a defence against raiding parties. The walls are double skinned, providing small rooms and storage areas between the inner and outer walls. Steps were also built in the gap between the walls. Sardinia has a very similar class of structure known as the Nuraghe.

items.name: Burial Chamber (Dolmen)
items.description: A megalithic chambered tomb, with a large flat stone laid on upright ones. Cromlech is a term meaning the same thing, archaic in English but still used in Welsh and Breton languages.

items.name: Cairn
items.description: A mound of stones, often but not always covering a burial site. See the separate category for Round Cairn. This category includes long cairns and other miscellaneous cairns.

items.name: Castro or Chafurdão
items.description: Castros (s. Castro) are a kind of settlement relatively common in northwestern Spain, composed of a fortified area (quite similar to the Irish or Scottish Stone Forts, but slightly bigger in area) with a multitude of stone round huts inside it. In some later castros the Roman influence may be seen in rectangular/square buildings within the settlement. In Portugal is a type of ancient construction called Chafurdão. It is a type of round house built in stone, very similar with the Iron Age houses of the castros. The big difference is that these constructions usually stand alone. These kind of monuments are found most of the time surrounded by stone walls, and some are strangely very close with rock cut graves. Some theorists believe they are related but it's almost impossible to prove that relationship.

items.name: Cave or Rock Shelter
items.description: A cave with evidence of inhabitation by Palaeolithic (Old Stone Age) Man.

items.name: Chambered Tomb
items.description: Megalithic tomb usually for multiple burials. Varieties include passage graves, gallery graves, portal dolmens.

items.name: Class I / Class II Hybrid Pictish Symbol Stone
Court Tomb
items.description: Irish variant of Burial Chamber.

items.name: Crannog
items.description: Artificial lakeside platform chosen as a settlement site.

items.name: Cursus
items.description: An avenue formed by straight stretches of parallel earthen banks and ditches. The longest, in Dorset, extends nearly 10 km. Found only in Britain.

items.name: Henge
items.description: Roughly circular prehistoric earthwork consisting of a non-defensive ditch and bank with a level plateau in the centre. A henge does not have to contain a stone circle but many do
Roughly circular prehistoric earthwork consisting of a non-defensive ditch and bank with a level plateau in the centre. A henge does not have to contain a stone circle but many do.

items.name: Hill Figure
items.description: A chalk-cut figure, unique to the British Isles. Not necessarily prehistoric, but of interest nonetheless.

items.name: Hillfort
items.description: Hilltop enclosure usually thought to be defensive. Most hillforts date from the Iron Age, although some are earlier.

items.name: Holed Stone
items.description: A megalith with a hole in it. These stones are usually associated with legends of magical cures that people who pass through them will benefit from.

items.name: Long Barrow
items.description: Elongated roughly rectangular structure that may contain many burial chambers. Long barrows appear to have been in constant use with burials being added over a period of centuries, the old bones being moved around to accommodate the new interment. It is thought that bones may even have been removed for ritual use, particularly the skulls and leg bones. See also the separate listing for chambered tomb.

items.name: Marker Stone
items.description: Prehistoric stones or other ancient stones (older than 1066) used as boundary or route markers.

items.name: Multiple Stone Rows / Avenue
items.description: Two or more rows of stones arranged in a complex. An avenue is two rows side by side.

items.name: Natural Stone / Erratic / Other Natural Feature
Passage Grave
items.description: Type of chambered tomb where a passage connects with one or more stone chambers in the centre of a mound.

items.name: Ring Cairn
items.description: Stone Burial Mound similar to Round Cairn, but with a hole in the centre. See also Clava Cairn.

items.name: Round Cairn
items.description: Stone Burial Mound similar to Round Barrow, but usually found in areas with thin top soil - the mound is formed by piling boulders into a hemispherical structure.

items.name: Souterrain (Fogou, Earth House)
items.description: Souterrain is the generic term for an underground prehistoric structure. Known as Earth House in Scotland, and Fogou (pronounced "foogoo") in Cornwall. Stone underground tunnel or chamber. Nobody knows what they were used for, though suggestions include food storage, cattle shelter, refuge against attackers and ritual use.

items.name: Standing Stone (Menhir)
items.description: A single standing stone.

items.name: Standing Stones
items.description: A pair, or other arrangement of stones. Three or more in a line are listed separately as stone row or rows.

items.name: Stone Circle
items.description: A ring of stones, sometimes at a henge. Distinct from a cairn circle, which is not a stone circle proper.

items.name: Stone Fort or Dun
items.description: A fortified stone structure. Dun is the gaelic word, as used in Scotland.

items.name: Stone Row / Alignment
items.description: A single row of three or more stones. Some of these can be hundreds of meters long.

items.name: Turf Maze
items.description: A maze cut in the grass. Not necessarily prehistoric, but of interest nonetheless.

items.name: Vitrified Fort
items.description: A stone fort (or dun) that has had some of its stones fused together by extremely high temperatures. How these stones came to be fused is a mystery!
